  <static seed="1437" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations1.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{70}{x}} = {7} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{10\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{x}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{70}{x}} \amp = {7} \\
   {\frac{70}{x}} \cdot x \amp = {7} \cdot x \\
   70 \amp = 7x \\
   \frac{70}{7} \amp = \frac{7 x}{7} \\
   10 \amp = x \\
   x \amp = 10
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>x \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>x = 10</m>.</p>
</solution>
